# 4. Query: `MT P&P (income)`

## Purpose
This query builds the **Postage & Packaging income** side of the Mosaic Trading journal.

It:
- filters only rows with `Postage & Packaging Description`
- derives BC dimensions and accounts
- maps posting date using `Bank_Date_Helper`
- groups rows
- calculates the grouped income amount
- reshapes the output into final journal format

---

## High-level flow

```text
Table2 source
→ keep only P&P rows
→ type and clean source columns
→ derive dimensions (project / year / appeal / department)
→ map account via VAT-PQ
→ assign posting date via Bank_Date_Helper
→ use Postage & Packaging Description as Amount
→ group rows
→ sum grouped amount
→ keep representative row values
→ reshape final journal output
```

---

## Block-by-block explanation

### Block 1 – Load source and filter to P&P rows

```m
Source = Excel.CurrentWorkbook(){[Name="Table2"]}[Content],

#"Filtered Rows" = Table.SelectRows(
    Source,
    each [#"Postage & Packaging Description"] <> null),
```

#### What it does
Loads `Table2` and keeps only rows where **`Postage & Packaging Description` is not null**.

#### Why it matters
This is how the query identifies which rows belong to the P&P journal stream.

#### Risks / gotchas

- If valid P&P rows sometimes have blank/null descriptions, they will be dropped.
- This means the source relies on that description field being the business identifier for P&P.

---

### Block 2 – Type source columns

```m
#"Changed Type" = Table.TransformColumnTypes(...)
```

#### What it does
Assigns data types to all core source columns, including:

- dates
- numbers
- marketing source code
- IDs

#### Why it matters
Required so later text parsing, joins, and sums work consistently.

#### Risks / gotchas

- Some fields are typed as `Int64.Type`, which can fail if later source data becomes mixed-format.
- If leading zeros matter anywhere, numeric typing may remove them.

---

### Block 3 – Basic renames and department lookup

```m
#"Changed Type1" = Table.TransformColumnTypes(#"Removed Columns",{{"Gift Date", type date}, {"NL post date", type date}}),
#"Renamed Columns" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Changed Type1",{{"Gift Date", "Posting date"}}),
#"Renamed Columns1" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Renamed Columns",{{"Reference", "Document No."}, {"Posting date", "Document Date"}}),
```

Then:

```m
#"Merged Queries" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Renamed Columns1", {"Department Code Description"}, #"DEP-PQ", {"RE data export name"}, "DEP-PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded DEP-PQ" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries", "DEP-PQ", {"BC Department Code"}, {"DEP-PQ.BC Department Code"}),
#"Renamed Columns2" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Expanded DEP-PQ",{{"DEP-PQ.BC Department Code", "Department Code"}}),
```

#### What it does
- Renames `Gift Date` into a staging `Document Date`
- Renames `Reference` into `Document No.`
- Maps `Department Code Description` into `Department Code`

#### Why it matters
This starts the conversion from source-native RE fields to Business Central-style posting fields.

#### Risks / gotchas
- There is a naming hop where `Gift Date` becomes `Posting date`, then immediately becomes `Document Date`. This is functionally okay but not very readable.
- Department code quality depends entirely on `DEP-PQ` key matching.

---

### Block 4 – Derive Project / Year / Appeal codes

```m
#"Inserted Text Before Delimiter" = Table.AddColumn(#"Renamed Columns2", "Project Code", each Text.BeforeDelimiter([Income Ref], " "), type text),
#"Inserted Text Range" = Table.AddColumn(#"Inserted Text Before Delimiter", "Text Range", each Text.Middle([Appeal ID], 6, 2), type text),
#"Added Conditional Column" = Table.AddColumn(#"Inserted Text Range", "Custom", each if [Text Range] = "00" then "NA" else [Text Range], type text),
#"Renamed Columns3" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Added Conditional Column",{{"Custom", "Year Code"}}),
#"Inserted Text Range1" = Table.AddColumn(#"Renamed Columns3", "Appeal Code", each Text.Middle([Appeal ID], 2, 4), type text),
```

#### What it does
Derives:
- `Project Code` from the first token in `Income Ref`
- `Year Code` from characters 6–7 of `Appeal ID`
- `Appeal Code` from characters 2–5 of `Appeal ID`

#### Why it matters
These are dimension fields used in grouping and final BC journal output.

#### Risks / gotchas
- All of these rely on strict source formatting.
- If `Income Ref` has no space, `Text.BeforeDelimiter` may fail.
- If `Appeal ID` format changes, codes can silently become wrong.

---

### Block 5 – Add account fields and VAT mapping

```m
#"Added Custom" = Table.AddColumn(#"Removed Columns5", "Bal. Account No.", each null),
#"Inserted Literal" = Table.AddColumn(#"Added Custom", "Document Type", each "PAYMENT", type text),
#"Added Custom1" = Table.AddColumn(#"Inserted Literal", "Major Appeal Code", each null),
```

Then:

```m
#"Merged Queries1" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Added Custom1", {"Gift subtype"}, #"VAT-PQ", {"Gift Subtype"}, "VAT-PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded VAT-PQ" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries1", "VAT-PQ", {"BC Destination Code"}, {"VAT-PQ.BC Destination Code"}),
#"Renamed Columns5_1" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Expanded VAT-PQ",{{"VAT-PQ.BC Destination Code", "Account No."}}),
```

#### What it does
- Adds placeholder balancing fields
- Sets `Document Type = PAYMENT`
- Looks up `Account No.` from `VAT-PQ` using `Gift subtype`

#### Why it matters
This is the main account-mapping step for P&P income rows.

#### Risks / gotchas
- `Gift subtype` should ideally be cleaned/normalised before this join, but in this query it is not explicitly standardised like in your Addition query.
- `Document Type` is later overwritten to null, so its current value is temporary.

---

### Block 6 – Build interim Description and assign Posting Date from helper

```m
#"Added Custom3" = Table.AddColumn(#"Removed Columns6", "dESCRIPTION", each Bank_Date_Helper[JG Prefix]{0}),
#"Inserted Merged Column" = Table.AddColumn(#"Added Custom3", "Description", each Text.Combine({[dESCRIPTION], " - ", Text.From([Marketing Source Code], "en-GB")}), type text),
#"Removed Columns1_1" = Table.RemoveColumns(#"Inserted Merged Column",{"dESCRIPTION", "Marketing Source Code", "Reference number", "Data Collection Source Description"}),
#"Added Custom4" = Table.AddColumn(#"Removed Columns1_1", "Posting Date", each Bank_Date_Helper[Date]{0}),
```

#### What it does
- Pulls a prefix from `Bank_Date_Helper`
- Builds an interim `Description`
- Sets a default `Posting Date` from `Bank_Date_Helper[Date]{0}`

#### Why it matters
This is where the query starts taking logic from the helper table rather than source gift data.

#### Risks / gotchas
- `Bank_Date_Helper[Date]{0}` means “take the first row’s date”, which is fragile if the helper table is not exactly the structure expected.
- The interim description is later replaced again.

---

### Block 7 – Override Posting Date based on paying-in-slip match

```m
#"Merged Queries4" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Reordered Columns", {"Paying In Slip Number Description"}, Bank_Date_Helper, {"Narrative #1"}, "Bank_Date_Helper", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded Bank_Date_Helper" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries4", "Bank_Date_Helper", {"Date"}, {"Bank_Date_Helper.Date"}),
#"Removed Columns12" = Table.RemoveColumns(#"Reordered Columns12",{"Posting Date"}),
#"Renamed Columns20" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Removed Columns12",{{"Bank_Date_Helper.Date", "Posting Date"}}),
```

#### What it does
Replaces the default posting date with a more specific posting date looked up by:

- source key: `Paying In Slip Number Description`
- helper key: `Bank_Date_Helper[Narrative #1]`

#### Why it matters
This is the real posting-date logic that should align journal rows to bank/helper narrative mapping.

#### Risks / gotchas
- If the paying-in-slip reference does not match helper narrative, `Posting Date` becomes null.
- This is one of the most likely real-world mismatch points.

---

### Block 8 – P&P amount logic

```m
#"Renamed Columns4" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Changed Type2",{{"Gf_Receipt_amount", "Amount"}, {"Donation Collection Fees Description", "Fees"}}),
```

Then later:

```m
#"Removed Columns2" = Table.RemoveColumns(#"Added Custom Column",{
    "Fees", "Amount", "Gift Amount", "Column1", "Custom"
}),

#"Renamed Columns8" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Removed Columns2",{{"Postage & Packaging Description", "Amount"}}),
```

#### What it does
This is important:
- the query temporarily renames `Gf_Receipt_amount` to `Amount`
- but later removes that `Amount`
- then **renames `Postage & Packaging Description` to `Amount`**

#### Why it matters
This means the **final income amount is actually sourced from `Postage & Packaging Description`**, not `Gf_Receipt_amount` or `Gift Amount`.

#### Risks / gotchas
- This is probably the single most important logic point in the whole query.
- If `Postage & Packaging Description` is a text-like or mixed field rather than a clean numeric value, this could create mismatches or implicit coercion issues.
- It can also be confusing, because earlier steps appear to suggest other amount fields matter more.

---

### Block 9 – Group rows and sum amount

```m
#"Grouped Rows" = Table.Group(
    #"Renamed Columns8",
    {
        "Posting Date",
        "Document Date",
        "Document No.",
        "Project Code",
        "Year Code",
        "Appeal Code",
        "Department Code"
    },
    {
        {"All", each _, type table [...]}
    }
),

#"Added Custom10" = Table.AddColumn(#"Grouped Rows", "Custom", each List.Sum([All][Amount])),
#"Added Custom11" = Table.AddColumn(#"Added Custom10", "Custom.1", each Table.FirstN([All], 1)),
```

#### What it does
- Groups rows by date/document/dimensions
- Sums grouped `Amount`
- Keeps the first row in each group as a template row for static values

#### Why it matters
This is the main aggregation logic for P&P income.

#### Risks / gotchas
- Any grouped field omitted here may cause rows to combine when they should remain separate.
- The first-row template pattern means some fields come from the first underlying row, not from a controlled aggregation rule.

---

### Block 10 – Final reshaping and field overwrites

This section is long, but the most important behaviours are:

#### A. Amount is multiplied by `-1`
```m
#"Multiplied Column" = Table.TransformColumns(#"Removed Columns7", {{"Custom", each _ * -1, type number}})
```
So grouped P&P income is output as **negative**.

#### B. External document number is created by duplicating `Document No.`
This is standard.

#### C. `Document Type` is reset to null
```m
#"Added Custom13" = Table.AddColumn(#"Renamed Columns16", "Document Type", each null)
```
So the earlier `PAYMENT` does **not** survive to the final output.

#### D. `Major Appeal Code` is mapped via `MA - PQ`
```m
#"Merged Queries3" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Renamed Columns17", {"Major Appeal Code"}, #"MA - PQ", {"RE Data Export Name"}, "MA - PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter)
```
But note: before that point, `Major Appeal Code` was null.
So this mapping may often produce null unless upstream data has been changed.

#### E. `Description` is overwritten
First:
```m
"Description" = "MT P&P - " & Text.From([Document Date], "en-GB")
```
Then `Document No.` is overwritten as:
```m
"MT - " & Text.From([Posting Date], "en-GB")
```

#### Why it matters
The final visible output is **not the same as the earlier descriptive staging logic**.

#### Risks / gotchas
- Several earlier fields are only staging fields and do not survive to the final output.
- This is easy to miss when debugging.

---

## Plain-English summary of `MT P&P (income)`

> This query filters Table2 to P&P rows, derives BC dimensions and account codes, assigns posting dates from `Bank_Date_Helper`, uses `Postage & Packaging Description` as the final amount source, groups rows, then outputs a negative-value journal line set with standard BC columns.

